es or dies by free speech can help guide students, faculty, administrators, and alumni when faced with unpopular, hateful, or dangerous speech. Timely and vitally important, Speak Freely shows why universities can succeed only by fostering more free speech, more free thought—and a greater tolerance for both.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAcademic freedomzUnited States. 0aEducation, HigherzUnited StatesxPhilosophy. 0aFreedom of speechzUnited States. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Censorship.2bisacsh  a1st Amendment.  aAlexander Meiklejohn.  aAllan Bloom.  aAmerican Civil Liberties Union.  aBari Weiss.  aBill Maher.  aFirst Amendment.  aJohn Stuart Mill.  aMcCarthyism.  aThe Closing of the American Mind.  aThe Coddling of the American Mind.  aacademic freedom.  acampus Republicans.  acampus diversity.  acancel culture.  acensorship on campus.  acensorship.  aconservatism.  afree expression.  afree speech on campus.  afreedom of speech.  aliberal indoctrination.  aliberalism.  aonline shaming.  apolitical correctness.  aspeech as violence.  astudent groups.  awoke McCarthyism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z97831106633650 cprintz978069119152240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691193595?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691193595423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780691193595/original  a978-3-11-066336-5  Princeton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK